 "ethical food" and "ethical eating" in socialist and formerly socialist societies. With essays by anthropologists, sociologists, and geographers, this politically nuanced volume offers insight into the origins of alternative food movements and their place in today's global economy. Collectively, the essays cover discourses on food and morality; the material and social practices surrounding production, trade, and consumption; and the political and economic power of social movements in Bulgaria, China, Cuba, Lithuania, Russia, and Vietnam. Scholars and students will gain important historical and anthropological perspective on how the dynamics of state-market-citizen relations continue to shape the ethical and moral frameworks guiding food practices around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFood consumptionxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aFood consumptionxSocial aspects. 0aFoodxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aFoodxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aAvieli, Nir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlumberg, Renata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Melissa L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldwell, Melissa L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJung, Yuson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJung, Yuson, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKlein, Jakob A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Jakob A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMincyte, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOxfeld, Ellen, econtribu